. As a founder of companies intended to solve big problems, Elon Musk has b=
een quite effective.
This is obvious stuff.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CElon Musk tackles big problems and is =
unusually good at solving them=E2=80=9D is just conventional wisdom, which =
is why there are=C2=A0glowing biographies written about him and=C2=A0some d=
ays he=E2=80=99s the richest person in the world. The main way to get reall=
y rich is by solving big problems successfully.
And that=E2=80=99s the third point that I want to make about this list: Whe=
n Elon Musk has looked around and identified a big problem and set about tr=
ying to solve it, he has done so by founding (or acquiring) a for-profit co=
mpany that he owns and controls.
  [2]
=C2=A0This is not the only way to (try to) solve big problems. Bill Gates, =
for instance, got very rich by selling software=C2=A0and then decided to im=
prove the world by donating a lot of money  to charitable works. Or various=
 billionaires try to improve the world by supporting politicians who they t=
hink will do good things. Musk has dabbled in these approaches, but mostly =
they are not his preference. =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98Most philanthropy was bulls=
=E2=80=94,=E2=80=99=C2=A0Musk told Gates=E2=80=9D once,=C2=A0arguing that T=
esla did more good for the world than most charities.
And this too is a pretty common view.=C2=A0It is not the only view =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0a lot of people think that philanthropy is good! =E2=80=94=C2=A0bu=
t in Silicon Valley tech circles it is  fairly conventional=C2=A0to  think =
that startups are a better way to improve the world than charity, that star=
tups can be more ambitious, more focused on results, have a better alignmen=
t of interests and more motivated employees, and can raise and deploy a lot=
 more money than charities. =E2=80=9CTechnological innovation in a market s=
ystem is inherently philanthropic,=E2=80=9D  wrote Marc Andreessen last yea=
r, in a =E2=80=9CTechno-Optimist Manifesto=E2=80=9D laying out this view.
Now, I don=E2=80=99t think that Musk thinks that=C2=A0all=C2=A0profit-seeki=
ng companies, or all=C2=A0tech startups, are good; he criticizes lots of th=
em, and had to go and buy Twitter because its previous management upset him=
. I just think that he thinks the best way to improve the world is generall=
y through=C2=A0a for-profit company that he runs. And even=C2=A0this=C2=A0v=
iew =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe highest form of philanthropy is a for-profi=
t company run specifically by Elon Musk=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0is pretty w=
idespread. Larry Page  has mused=C2=A0about=C2=A0leaving=C2=A0his fortune t=
o Musk, because Musk=E2=80=99s for-profit businesses are more philanthropic=
=C2=A0than any philanthropies he can think of.=C2=A0
Last week  Musk sued OpenAI, arguing that it was founded as a nonprofit org=
anization to build artificial intelligence for the benefit of humanity, tha=
t he was a big donor to that nonprofit, and that it has turned into a for-p=
rofit company in violation of a supposed agreement not to. What I find stra=
ngest about all this is that OpenAI was a nonprofit to begin with: Its foun=
ders, people like Musk and Sam Altman, are generally leading proponents and=
