When I worked as a mergers-and-acquisitions lawyer and then as an investmen=
t banker, I thought that you could trade stocks in the US=C2=A0from 9:30 a.=
m. to 4 p.m. New York time, Monday through Friday. Was that completely accu=
rate? No, of course not: There were, and still are,=C2=A0early morning and =
after-hours=C2=A0trading sessions, and I knew that.=C2=A0But it was close t=
o true: There was, and still is,=C2=A0much more trading during normal marke=
t hours than in the extended sessions.
And it was a=C2=A0very=C2=A0useful=C2=A0approximation of the truth. In part=
icular, here are two stylized facts that are sort of true and that work ver=
y nicely together:
=09=E2=80=9CThe market is closed evenings, early mornings and weekends.=E2=
=80=9D=09=E2=80=9CPublic companies have an obligation to keep their investo=
rs informed about material stuff that is going on.=E2=80=9D

For example: Public-company mergers and acquisitions tend to be intensively=
 negotiated over the weekend,=C2=A0and are often announced on Monday mornin=
gs.
  [4]
=C2=A0Why? Well, because if a public company reaches an agreement to sell i=
tself, that is an extremely material fact, and it should really announce th=
at right away. You do not want people blithely buying and selling the stock=
 at $35 when the company has already signed a merger agreement to sell itse=
lf for $50 per share. If you sign that deal at 11:46 a.m. on a Wednesday, f=
irst of all, every second that you spend drafting the press release is prec=
ious, and second, whenever that press release=C2=A0does=C2=A0come out, it=
=E2=80=99s going to be disruptive: The stock will spike up, people will mak=
e and lose fortunes, people who see=C2=A0the press release a=C2=A0milliseco=
nd=C2=A0before everyone else will have a huge advantage, and you will gener=
ally have disorderly and unpleasant trading. In fact, if you=C2=A0do find y=
ourself needing to announce a merger at 11:46 a.m. on a Wednesday, you will=
 ordinarily ask the stock exchange to halt trading in the stock first, and =
reopen it only after the announcement has gone out and everyone has had a f=
ew minutes to read it.
But that is stressful and disruptive too, and it=E2=80=99s much better to j=
ust get everything buttoned up on Sunday evening, get the press release rea=
dy to go, and put it out first thing Monday morning, well before the market=
 opens.
  [5]
=C2=A0Give everyone plenty of nontrading time to digest and understand the =
news, so that when trading starts everyone is on a level playing field. Als=
o, if for some reason there is a glitch in the system when you hit publish =
on the press release at 6 a.m.,=C2=A0you have=C2=A0time to fix it: If it go=
es out at 6:20, that=E2=80=99s fine too.
(To be clear, this stylized fact is=C2=A0good and useful from the abstract =
perspective of the public company, but it was very bad from my perspective =
as a young M&A lawyer. Terrible hours!)
Anyway, I mostly still think that
=09=E2=80=9Cmarket hours=E2=80=9D are 9:30 to 4, Monday through Friday,=09y=
ou are supposed to put out material news =E2=80=9Coutside of market hours,=
=E2=80=9D and=09it doesn=E2=80=99t matter all that=C2=A0much exactly when y=
ou do that, as long as you leave plenty of time before the market opens.

And I think=C2=A0a lot of other people still think that too, in part out of=
 old habit, and in part because it is still sort of true, and in part becau=
se it remains very useful.
But there has been some=C2=A0creep toward=C2=A0always-on financial markets =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0we  talked last week about a proposed 23-hour-a-day stock ex=
change =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I worry that this stylized fact is no longer=C2=
=A0true. We  talked a few weeks ago about a typo in Lyft Inc.=E2=80=99s ear=
nings release. Lyft put out the release right after the market closed on a =
Tuesday, there was a material typo, Lyft did an earnings call at 4:30 p.m.,=
 it verbally corrected the typo, and it filed a corrected earnings release =
at 5:51 p.m. Absolutely no harm, no foul, on the traditional way of thinkin=
g: All of this happened after hours, and by 9:30 the next morning everyone =
had had plenty of time to digest it.=C2=A0
But in fact $700 million worth of Lyft stock traded in the after-hours exte=
nded session=C2=A0that Tuesday, roughly three times as much as Lyft usually=
 trades in the=C2=A0regular=C2=A0trading session. And there were news stori=
es about it, and readers emailed me to be like =E2=80=9Cis this securities =
fraud,=E2=80=9D and Lyft=E2=80=99s CEO had to  go on television to say he w=
as sorry. I forgive him! I wrote:

It is customary to do these things after market hours for =E2=80=94 well, n=
ot exactly for this reason, but kind of for this reason? You put out the pr=
ess release just after the market=E2=80=99s regular trading session closes =
at 4 p.m., and investors have 17.5 hours to think about it before the marke=
t opens again at 9:30 a.m. the next day. They can ponder the earnings relea=
se at their leisure, update their models, ask questions on the earnings cal=
l, and generally take their time to digest the new information and formulat=
e a price view before the market opens and they have to trade on it. If the=
re=E2=80=99s anything ambiguous or surprising in the earnings release =E2=
=80=94 or a typo! =E2=80=94 the company and the investors have time to clar=
ify it, and they can trade the next day with well informed views. =E2=80=A6
Lyft can=E2=80=99t stop its shareholders from trading after hours, but in s=
ome rough sense that=E2=80=99s not its responsibility. If you want to trade=
 in the after-hours market the second the press release hits the tape, the =
risk of typos is on you.

And then=C2=A0last week Celsius=C2=A0did this:

Celsius Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s quarterly results were sitting online, wait=
ing to give anyone who looked a sneak peek at the earnings that would set o=
ff a 20% rally in the energy-drink company=E2=80=99s stock price.
Not many people, it seems, knew they were there.
The company, which has a market value of about $19 billion, was scheduled t=
o release its fourth-quarter and full-year results at 6 a.m. New York time =
on Thursday.
But they appeared on Celsius=E2=80=99s website Wednesday night shortly afte=
r 7 p.m., with screenshots later circulating on X. The stock edged higher a=
round that time, but on featherweight volumes. Trading picked up right at 6=
 a.m. Thursday, with shares falling more than 5% premarket before surging d=
uring the regular session by the most since August. They ended the day at a=
n all-time high. =E2=80=A6
It appears to be the latest blunder of what=E2=80=99s been a fairly gaffe-h=
eavy earnings season, with notable clerical errors in reports from Lyft Inc=
., Planet Fitness Inc., Mister Car Wash Inc. and Rivian Automotive Inc. ...
Of course, even if investors did see Celsius=E2=80=99s report when it becam=
e available Wednesday night, they may not have been able to trade on it at =
the time and would=E2=80=99ve waited until Thursday=E2=80=99s premarket ses=
sion, said Kenneth Polcari, chief market strategist at Slatestone Wealth LL=
C.
=E2=80=9CI think it=E2=80=99s just sloppy,=E2=80=9D Polcari said of the ear=
ly release. =E2=80=9CBut I don=E2=80=99t think anyone was disadvantaged.=E2=
=80=9D

It=E2=80=99s fine! This is how it=E2=80=99s supposed to work! There are two=
 sorts of time in the stock market:
=09From 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m., people are trading and every millisecond count=
s.
  [6]

=09From 4 p.m. to 9:30 a.m., and all weekend, time stops mattering: That wh=
ole stretch of 17.5 or 65.5 hours is effectively a single=C2=A0point, and t=
here is no meaningful difference between 7 in the evening and 6 the next mo=
rning.


If you put your earnings up on your website at 7 p.m. and then put them out=
 on a news wire at 6 a.m., that=E2=80=99s fine! Those times are the same ti=
me! You did exactly what you are supposed to do; you got=C2=A0the informati=
on out there in the quiet time between when the market closed and when it o=
pened=C2=A0again. Except=C2=A0the market was kind of=C2=A0open the whole ti=
me.

