The other day I mentioned a lawsuit against Crown Castle Inc., whose estran=
ged co-founder sued over a deal the company struck with Elliott Investment =
Management. Elliott had run an activist campaign and threatened a proxy fig=
ht, and Crown Castle settled by giving Elliott two board seats. The co-foun=
der, Ted Miller, wants to nominate his own board candidates=C2=A0and object=
ed to Crown Castle=E2=80=99s agreement to endorse Elliott's directors witho=
ut even considering his. =E2=80=9CThe affairs of Delaware corporations,=E2=
=80=9D his lawyers=C2=A0wrote, =E2=80=9Cmust be managed by boards of direct=
ors, not backroom deals.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Well, this week Crown Castle and Elliott amended their deal to add a =E2=80=
=9Cfiduciary out.=E2=80=9D That is: They still have a contract saying that =
the board will endorse Elliott=E2=80=99s nominees, but now the contract spe=
cifically says that the board can change its mind if it decides that that=
=E2=80=99s in the best interests of shareholders:
If the Board in good faith determines (a =E2=80=9CRecommendation Determinat=
ion=E2=80=9D), after consultation with counsel, that the fiduciary duties o=
f the members of the Board as directors of the Company require that the Boa=
rd (x) change or withhold a prior recommendation that the Company=E2=80=99s=
 shareholders vote =E2=80=9Cfor=E2=80=9D, or (y) recommend that the Company=
=E2=80=99s shareholders vote =E2=80=9Cagainst=E2=80=9D, the election of a N=
ew Director (a =E2=80=9CSpecified Director=E2=80=9D), then: [it can].
That does seem like a fairly straightforward fix. Miller=E2=80=99s objectio=
n was a technical point of Delaware law: The board of directors has to run =
the company in the way that it thinks is best for shareholders, so signing =
a contract saying =E2=80=9Cthe board will recommend your nominees=E2=80=9D =
might be illegal, if (1) the board later gets other nominees, (2) it decide=
s, in its heart of hearts, that those nominees are better, but (3) it feels=
 bound by the contract to recommend the first, worse nominees. But if you r=
ewrite the contract to say =E2=80=9Cthe board can change its mind,=E2=80=9D=
 that addresses the problem. And these outs are not uncommon. In particular=
, many=C2=A0public-company merger agreements let the target company=E2=80=
=99s board get out of the merger if, after jumping through some hoops, they=
 conclude that another deal is in the shareholders=E2=80=99 best interests.
Obviously rewriting the contract to say that the board can change its mind =
makes it a less useful contract. But the point is that, here, the board=C2=
=A0wanted=C2=A0the deal with Elliott, and probably=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0want Miller=E2=80=99s nominees on the board. Rewriting the contract solv=
es the technical problem but probably doesn=E2=80=99t change what will actu=
ally happen.

