lid; background-color: #ccc;">did this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Celsius Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s quarterly resu=
lts were sitting online, waiting to give anyone who looked a sneak peek at =
the earnings that would set off a 20% rally in the energy-drink company=E2=
=80=99s stock price.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not many people, it seems, knew they were ther=
e.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company, which has a market value of about=
 $19 billion, was scheduled to release its fourth-quarter and full-year res=
ults at 6 a.m. New York time on Thursday.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But they appeared on Celsius=E2=80=99s website=
 Wednesday night shortly after 7 p.m., with screenshots later circulating o=
n X. The stock edged higher around that time, but on featherweight volumes.=
 Trading picked up right at 6 a.m. Thursday, with shares falling more than =
5% premarket before surging during the regular session by the most since Au=
gust. They ended the day at an all-time high. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It appears to be the latest blunder of what=E2=
=80=99s been a fairly gaffe-heavy earnings season, with notable clerical er=
rors in reports from Lyft Inc., Planet Fitness Inc., Mister Car Wash Inc. a=
nd Rivian Automotive Inc. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course, even if investors did see Celsius=
=E2=80=99s report when it became available Wednesday night, they may not ha=
ve been able to trade on it at the time and would=E2=80=99ve waited until T=
hursday=E2=80=99s premarket session, said Kenneth Polcari, chief market str=
ategist at Slatestone Wealth LLC.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI think it=E2=80=99s just sloppy,=E2=
=80=9D Polcari said of the early release. =E2=80=9CBut I don=E2=80=99t thin=
k anyone was disadvantaged.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s fine! This is how it=E2=80=99s su=
pposed to work! There are two sorts of time in the stock market:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">From 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m., people are =
trading and every millisecond counts.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#f=
ootnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: non=
e !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-blo=
ck;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">From 4 p.m. to 9:30 a.m., and all=
 weekend, time stops mattering: That whole stretch of 17.5 or 65.5 hours is=
 effectively a single=C2=A0point, and there is no meaningful difference bet=
ween 7 in the evening and 6 the next morning.</li>
</ol>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
></ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you put your earnings up on your website at=
 7 p.m. and then put them out on a news wire at 6 a.m., that=E2=80=99s fine=
! Those times are the same time! You did exactly what you are supposed to d=
o; you got=C2=A0the information out there in the quiet time between when th=
e market closed and when it opened=C2=A0again. Except=C2=A0the market was k=
ind of=C2=A0open the whole time.</p>
