<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other day <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/34589760.257369/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMjkvdGhlLWJvYXJkLW9mLWRpcmVjdG9ycy1pcy1pb=
i1jaGFyZ2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwNjI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1f=
c291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMzA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZ=
m/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3f9fc7b3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">I mentioned</a> a lawsuit agai=
nst Crown Castle Inc., whose estranged co-founder sued over a deal the comp=
any struck with Elliott Investment Management. Elliott had run an activist =
campaign and threatened a proxy fight, and Crown Castle settled by giving E=
lliott two board seats. The co-founder, Ted Miller, wants to nominate his o=
wn board candidates=C2=A0and objected to Crown Castle=E2=80=99s agreement t=
o endorse Elliott's directors without even considering his. =E2=80=9CThe af=
fairs of Delaware corporations,=E2=80=9D his lawyers=C2=A0wrote, =E2=80=9Cm=
ust be managed by boards of directors, not backroom deals.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, this week Crown Castle and Elliott <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34589760.257369/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNTE0NzAvMDAwMDk1MDE0MjI0MD=
AwNjE4L2VoMjQwNDU0MDg2X2V4MTAwMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6d0304c6" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">amended their deal</a> to add a =E2=80=9Cfiduciary out.=E2=80=9D That=
 is: They still have a contract saying that the board will endorse Elliott=
=E2=80=99s nominees, but now the contract specifically says that the board =
can change its mind if it decides that that=E2=80=99s in the best interests=
 of shareholders:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the Board in good faith determi=
nes (a =E2=80=9CRecommendation Determination=E2=80=9D), after consultation =
with counsel, that the fiduciary duties of the members of the Board as dire=
ctors of the Company require that the Board (x) change or withhold a prior =
recommendation that the Company=E2=80=99s shareholders vote =E2=80=9Cfor=E2=
=80=9D, or (y) recommend that the Company=E2=80=99s shareholders vote =E2=
=80=9Cagainst=E2=80=9D, the election of a New Director (a =E2=80=9CSpecifie=
d Director=E2=80=9D), then: [it can].</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That does seem like a fairly straightforward f=
ix. Miller=E2=80=99s objection was a technical point of Delaware law: The b=
oard of directors has to run the company in the way that it thinks is best =
for shareholders, so signing a contract saying =E2=80=9Cthe board will reco=
mmend your nominees=E2=80=9D might be illegal, if (1) the board later gets =
other nominees, (2) it decides, in its heart of hearts, that those nominees=
 are better, but (3) it feels bound by the contract to recommend the first,=
 worse nominees. But if you rewrite the contract to say =E2=80=9Cthe board =
can change its mind,=E2=80=9D that addresses the problem. And these outs ar=
e not uncommon. In particular, many=C2=A0public-company merger agreements l=
et the target company=E2=80=99s board get out of the merger if, after jumpi=
ng through some hoops, they conclude that another deal is in the shareholde=
rs=E2=80=99 best interests.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously rewriting the contract to say that t=
he board can change its mind makes it a less useful contract. But the point=
 is that, here, the board=C2=A0<em>wanted=C2=A0</em>the deal with Elliott, =
and probably=C2=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>want Miller=E2=80=99s nomin=
ees on the board. Rewriting the contract solves the technical problem but p=
robably doesn=E2=80=99t change what will actually happen.</p>
